I thought it was weird that dawn and dusk don't have more birdstrikes than when it is daytime. I would think it's easier for a bird to miss a big airplane when it's sunny and not changing brightness.

Of course birds follow some sort of migratory pattern that can be seen in the increase of birdstrikes during Aug-Oct.

Aug and Sep look like they are very expensive months for Coster_Other during the dusk and night time, respectively. 

I'm surprised approach had a lot of strikes but was less costly to fix than the ones in the climb phase.
